article.description: Michelle Van Gorp sparked Minnesota to a first-half lead and Katie Smith's second-half shooting preserved it as the team snapped a seven-game losing streak.
article.headline: Lynx end seven-game skid
article.linkText: Lynx outpace Starzz to end seven-game skid
article.story:
MINNEAPOLIS (AP) -- Michelle Van Gorp sparked Minnesota to a first-half lead and Katie Smith's second-half shooting preserved it as the team snapped a seven-game losing streak.

Smith scored 20 points and Van Gorp had 18 as the Lynx beat Utah
70-62 Wednesday night.

"The key was that we had different people step up at different times,'' said new Lynx coach Heidi VanDerveer, who won for the first time in three tries.

Van Gorp, a center whose previous career best was 16 points at
Utah in 2000, scored 10 points in the first half, leading Minnesota
to a 32-22 lead.

Smith scored 17 points in the second half.

Utah (16-8) lost for just the second time in its last eight games. "We just didn't match their energy or intensity,'' Starzz coach Candi Harvey said.

The Lynx (7-15) fought off a late run by the Starzz, who trailed
by as many as 15 points in the second half. Utah pulled to 64-60
with 45 seconds to play, but Minnesota hit four free throws to put
the game out of reach.

"We knew they'd run at us in the second half, but we held them off,'' VanDerveer said.

Marie Ferdinand and Jennifer Azzi each scored 13 points for the Starzz.

"We got off to a slow start and it cost us,'' Ferdinand said.
